WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.120
These are 10 tips for beginners starting with Python and data science.

00:00:03.120 --> 00:00:05.320
Number one is to start messy and then get better.

00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:06.800
You don't need to write perfect code.

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:08.080
You just need to get things working.

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:09.240
You'll learn how to clean it up later.

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:11.640
Number two is to use Jupyter Notebooks for learning.

00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:14.520
Jupyter is a beginner friendly because it lets you run code in chunks

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:15.760
and see output instantly.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:18.360
Number three is AI is your coding copilot.

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:20.360
Literally everyone Googles error messages.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:23.600
So don't be afraid to copy code as long as you're trying to understand it too.

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:25.480
Number four is to start with real data.

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:27.440
Don't waste too much time on toy data sets.

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:30.400
Grab something interesting from Kaggle, UCI, or Tidy Tuesday

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:32.200
and try to answer a question you care about.

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:34.959
And number five is to master these libraries early.

00:00:34.959 --> 00:00:39.119
You got to get comfortable working with Pandas, Matplotlib, Seaborn, and scikit-learn.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:42.240
Number six is build one solid portfolio project.

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:46.000
Pick a data set, define a problem, clean it, analyze it, and maybe try a basic model.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.320
Number seven is GitHub is your resume.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:50.880
Upload your notebooks or projects and then write a simple readme.

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:52.360
The recruiters will look at this.

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:54.240
Number eight is don't rush into deep learning.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.759
Start with statistics, regression, or decision trees.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:00:59.880
You'll understand neural networks way better if you have a strong foundation.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:01.560
Number nine is learn by explaining.

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:05.080
Make slides, record a loom, or write a short blog post about something you learned.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:08.320
And lastly, number ten is to join a data science community.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:10.839
There are plenty of Slack groups, school clubs, discords,

00:01:10.839 --> 00:01:13.639
and being around others on the same path will help level you up faster.

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:16.400
Leave any questions in the comments below and follow along for more data science content.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:18.400
Bye!

